Bootstrap

Recall in HW01, Exercise 2.14, you simulated

  • \(n\) observations from a Normal\((0,1)\) random variable
  • used a qqplot and a histogram to evaluate how normal the observations looked

\(n=15\)

\(n=100\)

\(n=1000\)

Moral of the Story

If the sample size \(n\) is big, then the empirical distribution

Moral of the Story

well approximates the true population distribution.

Bootstrap Motivation

We want to make statements about the sampling distribution of some statistic based on samples of size \(n\) from some population distribution.

Bootstrap Motivation

Typically we won't know the true population distribution…

Bootstrap Motivation

… but we'll have a sample from it:

Bootstrap Motivation

Then resampling with replacement from the empirical distribution (left) approximates sampling from the true population distribution (right).

Example 1: We know result

Ex. where we know the result. Let the population distribution be Normal\((\mu=23, SD=7)\)…

Example 1: We know result

from which you draw a sample of size \(n=50\). We have \(\overline{x}\) = 22.181 and:

Example 1: We know result

We know the sampling distribution of \(\overline{X}\) is Normal\((\mu=23, SD=7/\sqrt{50}=0.99)\):

Example 1: We know result

Run the algorithm:

boot_sample_means <- rep(0, 10000)

for(i in 1:10000){
  boot_resample <- sample(x, replace = TRUE)
  boot_sample_means[i] <- mean(boot_resample)
}

Example 1: We know result

The bootstrap distribution of \(\overline{X}\)…

Example 1: We know result

… is similar in shape and spread as the true sampling distribution but …

Example 1: We know result

… it is not centered at \(\mu=23\), rather at \(\overline{x}\) = 22.181.

Example 2: We don't know result

Now say we want to know the sampling distribution of a wacky statistic:

  • \(T(\vec{X}) = \frac{\max(\vec{X}) - \min(\vec{X})}{\text{median}(\vec{X})}\)
  • with \(X_i \sim\) Normal\((\mu=27, \sigma=7)\) IID RV
  • and \(n=5000\)

Example 2: We don't know result

There is no result for what the sampling distribution of \(T(\overline{X})\) is, or at least, it's hard to derive. So we create the bootstrap distribution:

Example 2: We don't know result

boot_sample_WTF <- rep(0, 10000)

for(i in 1:10000){
  boot_resample <- sample(x, replace = TRUE)
  
  boot_sample_WTF[i] <- 
    (max(boot_resample) - min(boot_resample)) /
    median(boot_resample)
}

Example 2: We don't know result

The the shape and spread of bootstrap distribution of \(\overline{X}\) will be similar to the shape and spread of the sampling distribution.

Example 2: We don't know result

  • it is "centered" at \(T(\vec{x})\) = 2.21
  • it has SD = 0.082. i.e. the estimate of SE\([T(\vec{X})]\) is 0.082.
